##U.S. stocks ride out worst week since financial crisis, fed says

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

This is Sun Mingwei reporting for the paper

The Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped more than 1,000 points at one point on Feb. 28, when the three major U.S. stock indexes opened sharply lower on concerns about the spread of the epidemic, but the Federal Reserve said it would take appropriate measures to boost the economy, and Microsoft led a rally in big tech stocks, which recovered some of their losses.

By the close, the S & P 500 was down 24.60, or 0.83 percent, at 2,954.14; the Nasdaq was up 0.90, or 0.01 percent, at 8,567.37; and Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 357.50, or 1.39 percent, at 25,409.15. Eight of the 11 sectors in the S & P 500 fell and three rose. Among them, the utility sector led the decline, the energy sector led the rise.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
U.S. stocks posted their worst week since the 2008 financial crisis. The Dow has fallen more than 12 per cent this week, its biggest weekly percentage drop since 2008, and 14.1 per cent from its record high on February 12, when it was down more than 3,500 points by points. The S & P 500 is down 11.5% this week, its biggest weekly drop since the financial crisis.

Big U.S. tech stocks were mixed, with apple down 0.06% , Amazon down 0.03% , netflix down 0.72% , google up 1.85% , Facebook up 1.43% , microsoft up 2.42% and tesla down 1.62% .

Most of the popular stocks rose, with alibaba up 1.49% , JD.com up 0.29% and baidu up 0.06% , tiger tooth live up 7% , sogou up 6.8% , 360 finance up 6.09% and pinduoduo up 1.71% , danone technology down 31.87% , ninth city down 20% and wuyou english down 14.73% , ulai fell 0.36 per cent.

European stocks extended this week's historic sell-off in trading on Friday. The Stoxx Europe 600 index fell 13.80 points, or 3.54% , to 375.65, its biggest weekly decline since the height of the global financial crisis in October 2008. Germany's DAX 30 index fell 3.86% to 11,890.35, Britain's FTSE 100 index fell 3.18% to 6,580.61, FRANCE'S CAC 40 index fell 3.38% to 5,309.90 and Italy's FTSE MIB index fell 3.58% to 21,984.21.

The new coronavirus continues to circulate globally, with more than 82,000 confirmed cases and more than 2,800 deaths. World Health Organization director-general Tan Desai February 28 announced that the new pneumonia epidemic global risk level from the previous "high" to "very high.

The global spread of new-crown pneumonia has added to the jitters, but the Fed's no-brainer statement has given the markets a shot in the arm.

Fed Chairman Jerome Powell said Feb. 28 that the Fed is monitoring the risks posed by COVID-19 to the U.S. economy and is committed to taking action if necessary.

"The fundamentals of the U.S. economy are still strong, " Powell said. However, the COVID-19 poses an evolving risk to economic activity. The Fed is watching closely for developments and their impact on the economic outlook. We will use our tools and take appropriate action to support the economy."

The actual language in the statement was little different from previous statements by Powell and other Fed officials.

However, U.S. stocks and spot gold and silver pared losses after Powell's comments reassured markets that a vicious fall in the stock market and fears that the spread of the new coronavirus could threaten global economic growth, the dollar index came under pressure.

"I want the Fed to get involved, and I want them to get involved as soon as possible, " Donald Trump said late Friday afternoon.

Donald Trump did not specifically ask for a rate cut, but he said the Fed should follow its "big money" global peers as fears grew that the epidemic would lead to a sharp slowdown.

"They all put a lot of money into it. Our Fed is sitting there, not doing what they're supposed to be doing, " Donald Trump said. "They're doing a lot of damage to our country. "

Goldman Sachs said on Friday that the outbreak could have knocked 0.5 percentage points off global GDP in the first quarter and 0.2 percent in the second, and spurred the Federal Reserve and other central banks around the world to cut interest rates. Goldman Sachs expects the Fed to cut interest rates for the first time this year, probably in March, and by a total of 75 basis points in the first half.

Bank of America economists now expect the Fed to cut rates by 50 basis points at its March meeting to stem market panic and support growth. Whether or not to make an emergency cut before the meeting will depend on the extent of market failure.

"One of the biggest problems with this sell-off is probably that it came at the end of the month, " Kent Engelke, Chief Economic Strategist at Capitol Securities Management, said in an interview on Friday, "I really don't think many people are aware of the 'holocaust' that is taking place. The question is, how will people react when they see their monthly bill on March 1? "

"In terms of heightened investor sentiment, [ The outbreak ] came at The worst possible time, " said Doug Aaron Ramsey, chief investment officer at The Leuthold Group, a minneapolis-based investment research firm, of The new coronavirus outbreak, "I'm not sure the market has really absorbed the potential economic impact of this. "

Analysts at Unicredit said it may need clear signs that the number of confirmed new coronavirus cases is leveling off before the stock market bottoms out. But according to the latest statistics, that looks unlikely to happen in the next few days. As the stock market slump intensified, treasury and other core government bonds rose, driving down yields that move in the opposite direction to bond prices. "As a result, the stock market plunge, and the subsequent sustained decline in US and German bond yields, is likely not over, " unicredit analysts wrote in a research note

This issue is edited by Chang Chen
